1. Hyperedges — multi-way relationships

Graph theory extended ordinary edges (A—B) into hyperedges.

Instead of:

A — B

you get:

{A, B, C, D}

A single relationship can connect many nodes simultaneously.

Example:

R(A, B, C)

means a relation involving all three at once.

This is already how databases, knowledge graphs, and logic systems represent meaning.

It’s closer to language.

Example:

Give(Alice, Bob, Book)


